    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Humulus lupulus are humulone, lupulone, xanthohumol, 8-prenylnaringenin, and caryophyllene. Humulone and lupulone, two sesquiterpene acids, exhibit antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties, contributing to the plant's potential in wound healing and antimicrobial therapy. Xanthohumol, a prenylated flavonoid, has been shown to possess antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and anti-cancer properties, highlighting its potential in protecting against oxidative stress and cell damage. 8-prenylnaringenin, a prenylated flavonoid, has been found to have estrogenic activity, making it a potential therapeutic agent for menopausal symptoms and osteoporosis. Caryophyllene, a sesquiterpene, exhibits anti-inflammatory and analgesic properties, further supporting the plant's potential in pain management and inflammation reduction.",
